bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The National Education Association (NEA) is the largest professional organization and largest labor union in the United States, representing public school teachers and other support personnel, faculty and staffers at colleges and universities, retired educators, and college students preparing to become teachers. In 2010, the NEA had 3.2 million members and is located in Washington, D.C. The group holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code granted in 1906.

The NEA describes itself as a professional employee organization. The mission of the National Education Association is "to advocate for education professionals and to unite our members and the nation to fulfill the promise of public education to prepare every student to succeed in a diverse and interdependent world."

The NEA is a volunteer-based organization that relies upon its members to perform much of the Association's work. The members are supported by staff at the local, state, and national levels with the stated goal of "building great public schools for every student."

In 1857, Thomas W. Valentine, president of the New York State Teachers Association, issued a nation-wide invitation to teachers to unite in Philadelphia behind a common voice for America's growing public school system. After the meeting, the National Teachers Association (NTA) was formed with a membership of about 100. Minority educators were allowed to join at the start, but women were not allowed to join until 1866.

In 1870, the NTA merged with the American Normal School Association, the National Association of School Superintendents, and the Central College Association renaming itself the National Education Association. For the first 100 years of its existence, the NEA was controlled by administrators, and worked to further the interests of the "education profession" as a whole.
In the 1960's, after the first passage of a collective bargaining law for public employees, the NEA adopted union activities in addition to its operations as a professional association.
The NEA merged with the American Teachers Association (ATA), formerly the National Association of Teachers in Colored Schools (NATCS) in 1966.

In 1998, a proposed merger with the American Federation of Teachers (AFT) failed when it was rejected by NEA's Representative Assembly. Several NEA state affiliates have merged with their AFT counterparts, effectively forming a single association.

Over the years, the NEA has been a leader in national education reform and improvement movements. It has worked to improve the education provided to American school children through lobbying and campaigning on the local and national level as well as by promoting strong teacher education programs and continuous professional assessment and development.The National Education Association (NEA) is the largest professional organization and largest labor union in the United States, representing public school teachers and other support personnel, faculty and staffers at colleges and universities, retired educators, and college students preparing to become teachers. scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection documents the committees of the NEA. The collection contains twenty-six series reflecting the bodies and their records. The twenty-six series are: the Citizenship Committee, Committee of Constitutional Compliance, Committee on Educational Finance, Committee on International Relations, Compliance Committee, Committee on Planning and Organizational Development, Committee on Professional Ethics, Committee on Tenure and Academic Freedom, Committee on Women's Concerns, Committee Reports, Copyright Committee, Joint Committee of the NEA and American Legion, Joint Committee of the NEA and American Library Association, Joint Committee of the NEA and American Medical Association, Joint Committee of the NEA and American Teachers Association, Joint Committee of the NEA and Magazine Publishers Association, Joint Committee of the NEA and National Congress of Parents and Teachers, Joint Committee of the NEA and National School Board Association, Legislation Committee, Resolutions Committee, Special Services Committee, Standing Committee on Benefits, Standing Committee on National Public Relations, Streamlining Committee, Committee on Credit Unions, and Joint Committee of the NEA and Association of American Publishers.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The collection is organized into roughly alphabetical series based upon the NEA's organization. Records have been allocated largely to their offices of origin and reflect the work done within the offices, departments, divisions and units. Due to the immense size of the collection and the constraints placed upon the finding aid by the archival management system utilized by George Washington University, the collection was further divided up into parts.

Organized into 26 Series. Citizenship Committee; Committee on Constitutional Compliance; Committee on Educational Finance; Committee on International Relations; Committe on Planning and Organizational Development; Committee on Professional Ethics; Committee on Tenure and Academic Freedom; Committee on Women's Concerns; Committee Reports; Compliance Committee; Copyright Committee; Joint Committee of the NEA and the American Legion; Joint Committee of the NEA and American Library Association; Joint Committee and American Medical Association; Joint Committee of the NEA and American Teachers Association; Joint Committee of the NEA and Magazine Publishers Association; Joint Committee of the NEA and National Congress of Parents and Teachers; Joint Committee of the NEA and National School Board Association; Legislation Committee; Resolution Committee; Special Services Committee; Standing Committee on Benefits; Standing Committee on National Public Relations; Streamlining Committee; Committee on Credit Unions; Joint Committee of the NEA and Association American Publishers.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research. Some files are restricted. Those files flagged as restricted are subject to review by Special Collections staff before being made available for research. As researchers request materials, a review of the documents will take place. Staff will remove any documents with social security numbers, employee numbers or other sensitive identifying information. Any document found including this information is closed for 90 years from date of creation, or until verifiable proof of a person's death is given. After these documents are removed the folder will be available for research. In some cases, items may be photocopied and redacted. The redacted copy will then be placed in the publicly available folder. All other materials in a folder will be freely available for immediate use and will be marked as having been reviewed by Special Collections staff. After folders have been reviewed using these procedures and the confidential materials have been removed, the restriction shall be lifted.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created within the Citizenship Committee. The files include agenda books from meetings, conference papers, form letter books, reports and publications, Lucille Ellison's papers and conference planning papers of the National Conference on Citizenship.

These files cover many interesting issues involving the national identity around WWII and how to include patriotism and American civics into the classroom. The National Conference on Citizenship papers illustrate the strong partnership between the U.S. Department of Justice and the NEA in encouraging American studies in the classroom. This subseries provides great source material for studying the intersection of American Patriotism, Civics and education during the 1940s-1950s.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Citizenship Committee was one of the first committees created by the NEA in 1935. Its initial purpose was to study the requirements for schools in preparing students to be active citizens. Later the committee was involved with introducing voting rights and lowering the voting age to 18.

The committee also co-sponsored an annual conference with the Department of Justice called the National Conference on Citizenship. The committee also encouraged teachers to pursue political causes and to hold office.

From 1963-1970, the committee held regional political clinics throughout the U.S. In 1969, the committee recommended that a national political action committee be formed, but it was initially turned down. In 1970, it was reconsidered, and eventually created in 1972. This sealed the end of the committee.
"The National Education Association: The Power Base for Education" by Allan M. West, 1980.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: In 1938, the Committee on Tax Education and School Finance was founded. In 1959, the committee was renamed the Committee on Educational Finance.

The committee was very small and had limited funding but was noted for its publishing of a study on federal lands by Rasmussen, and its school finance systems statements. In 1956, greater funding was made available and the committee issued more publications and began to host an annual spring finance conference.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created within the Committee on Educational Finance. The files include papers for publication, minutes of meetings, and school finance statements.

The school finance statements files are the highlight of these records and track the economic viability of school systems within a state. The files cover the years 1941-1956 and provide great insight into the financial issues of the day, the effects of state-by-state solutions, and the general financial health of education during this time.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Committee on International Relations was established in 1920. The committee was formed to help with educational exchange activities, to work with the UNESCO National Commission, to prepare information kits on world affairs, and to maintain a liaison with other interested groups in education and world affairs. The committee was dissolved in 1972.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The planned Constitutional Convention in the early 1970s led to the creation of four committees including the Committee on Planning and Organizational Development (CPOD).

The CPOD was created in 1969 to consider what school conditions would be like in 5, 10, or more years in the future and the programs that would be needed. These expectations would help shape the revision of the constitution to ensure its applicability in the years ahead.
After the convention and the need for the projections waned, the committee was disbanded in 1975.
"The National Education Association: The Power Base for Education" by Allan M. West, 1980.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created within the Committee on Professional Ethics. The files include agenda books, papers regarding the code of ethics, investigations of ethics violations, "Opinions", and publications.

The investigations files provide cases studies surrounding individuals accused of ethics violations in the field of education. The files can be quite robust and detailed. Also of particular note are the "Opinions" written by the committee. These items were featured in the NEA newsletter and discussed an anonymous scenario based on real life in which professional ethics were questioned. These items provide the researcher a valuable insight into issues of the day and the common stance taken by those in the education field.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Committee on Professional Ethics was formed in 1924. The committee was formed to prepare a code of ethics for the teaching profession, to publicize it, to render opinions, and to answer requests for advice pertaining to action or contemplated action in this field.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Committee on Tenure and Academic Freedom was appointed in 1919, and was made up of five members, three of whom were classroom teachers. The committee was responsible to make known legislation that may curtail freedom in teaching, investigate cases of teacher discharge in violation of academic freedoms and assist them in finding new employment, and cooperate with other organizations that strive to maintain the principles of academic freedom.
The Committee was dissolved in June 1961, with its duties and responsibilities being passed to the newly created Commission on Professional Rights and Responsibilities.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created by the Copyright Committee. The files include materials from Harry N. Rosenfield and Harold Wigren and others. The papers include presentations to the U.S. Senate and House of Representatives, reactions to policy papers, speeches, and materials from the International Copyright Panel and the Copyright Task Force.

These records provide excellent insight into the priorities and areas of interest in copyright law as it regards education. Recording satellite television and the reuse of materials in the classroom are examined in context of copyright law at the time, and arguments are made to modify the laws in favor of educational use.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The copyright committee was formed as a result of ACT and Legislative Commission legislative activity seeking to influence and help direct the US government's revision of the 1909 copyright law.

The committee proposed that the 1909 copyright laws restricted the tools available for use in the classroom, and sought revisions to make more materials available in teaching. The revisions would include provisions for fair use and not-for-profit use of copyrighted materials so teachers and institutions may have right to make limited copies of materials.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Legislation Committee serves as the federal legislative agency and clearinghouse for the NEA. The committee formulates and recommends federal legislative policy for consideration, interprets application of adopted federal policy, formulates and evaluates action policies, and serves as the clearinghouse for all federal legislative objectives and programs of the NEA.

The Legislative Commission began in 1935, focusing on the fight for general federal aid legislation and records one of its first victories as the repeal of the "little red rider" to the 1935 DC salary appropriation bill. In 1972, the Legislative Committee was established to absorb the functions of the Legislative Commission and the Citizenship Committee under one body.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Special Services Committee was created in 1967. The committee consists of nine members appointed by the President, with approval of the Executive Committee. Each member serves for 5 years.

In 1967, it was proposed that the NEA Insurance Trust and the Special Services Committee merge to recommend general policy guidelines, and establish a more efficient and effective structure for the Special Services Division.
The responsibilities of this committee include:

1. Developing and recommending adoption of the Annual Budget for the Special Services Division. 2. Recommending general policy guidelines for the operation of the Special Services Division 3. Exercising general review and supervision over the operation and administration of special services programs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created within the Special Services Committee. The files include agenda books, meeting minutes, and NEA Insurance Reports to the Committee.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Standing Committee on National Public Relations was established in 1978. The committee had four objectives for its work:
1. To promote education as a national priority. 2. To promote the public's image of teachers. 3. To improve the teacher's image of themselves. 4. To improve NEA visibility.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Streamlining Committee or the Special Committee on Organizational Streamlining was created in 1989. The Committee was charged to examine the policies, structure, programs, and services of the NEA and make changes to involve more diverse membership groups and ensure responsiveness to their needs.
A final report and recommendations were introduced in 1991, and acted upon by the 1992 Representative Assembly. The Committee was scheduled to be disbanded in 1991.

scopecontent.p: Series contains materials created within the Streamlining Committee. The files include memoranda, meeting materials, and files on the Special Committee on Relationships with Other Organizations (SCROO).

bioghist.head: Historical note
bioghist.p: The Committee on Credit Unions was formed in 1937 as a special group, before being reclassified as a standing committee in 1940. The Committee was formed to keep members of the teaching profession informed as to the value of a credit union, to help members of the profession make efficient use of the resources available to them, and ultimately to make available credit union service to every school employee in the United States.
Source: 1954-55 NEA Handbook

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Committee on Employee Advocacy is responsible for proposing policies and activities to achieve a pluralistic education workforce and advance the economic interests, protect job security, improve the terms and conditions of employment, and secure the right to collective bargaining for all education employees.

The committee advises the Association on ways to improve national, state, and local cooperation in cooperation in coordinated advocacy efforts to achieve specific objectives in such areas as health care, employee compensation and benefits, and bargaining and organizing strategies.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Education and Library Networks Coalition (EdLiNC) is a coalition of 32 national organizations representing public and private schools and libraries. It was formed in 1995 to pass and implement the E-Rate program, a program intended to makes telecommunications and information services more affordable for schools and libraries..
Source: https://www.edlinc.org/ accessed January 4, 2019

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The series consists of material created or held by the Coalition. This includes reports, press releases, presentations, and other materials intended to be released to the public, as well as internal communications and statistics gathering in support of EdLiNC.
